g.text: GERALD R. MASSIE/State Historical Society of Missouri
May 20, 1770: The Spanish government officially assumed control of the Territory of Louisiana.
April 30, 1803: The Louisiana Purchase was signed in Paris.
May 14, 1804: The Lewis and Clark Expedition set out from St. Louis.
March 3, 1805: The Territory of Louisiana was established. James Wilkinson became the first governor of the territory.
Jan. 8, 1818: The first petition was presented to congress from Missouri requesting statehood.

g.text: Jan. 11, 1822: A bill was adopted to create the Missouri State Seal.
April 14, 1841: The University of Missouri, the first state university west of the Mississippi River, opened.

March 6, 1857: The Dred Scott decision was handed down by U.S. Chief Justice Roger B. Taney. The case originated in St. Louis. Under Missouri statutes in 1846, Scott was allowed to sue for his freedom from slavery because he had lived in Wisconsin, a free territory, beforereturning to the slave state of Missouri.

Jan. 11, 1865: Slavery was abolished in Missouri by an ordinance of immediate emancipation. Missouri was the first slave state to emancipate enslaved peoplebefore the adoption of the 13th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution.
Sept. 9, 1901: The first State Fair held in Sedalia opened.
April 30, 1904: The 1904 World’s Fair opened in St. Louis.

g.text: July 2, 1919: Missouri became the eleventh state to ratify the Nineteenth Amendment granting suffrage to women.

g.text: Dec. 12, 1938: The U.S. Supreme Court ruled in the absence of an equal law school for Black students, Lloyd Gaines should be admitted to the MU law school.
March 5, 1946: British Prime Minister Winston Churchill delivered his "Iron Curtain" speech at Westminster College in Fulton.

g.text: May 22, 2011: An EF-5 scale tornado destroyed one-third of Joplin, killing as many as 158 people with eight indirect deaths.
April 6, 1866: Lincoln Institute, later Lincoln University, was incorporated as an institution for Black students in Missouri.
April 9, 1682: Explorer Robert Cavalier, Sieur de La Salle took possession of the Louisiana Territory area for France.
A painting by Frank Nuderscher for Boatman’s Bank in St. Louis shows Laclede and Chouteau landing in St. Louis in 1763.

July 4, 1851: Groundbreaking ceremonies for the construction of the Pacific Railroad were held in St. Louis. The line was to go from St. Louis to Jefferson City and then to some point on the western boundary.

Oct. 1, 1812: The first general assembly of the Territory of Missouri met. The five original counties were organized: Cape Girardeau, New Madrid, St. Charles, St. Louis and Ste. Genevieve.
